In the current trend towards personalized and precision medicine, the pursuit of individualized treatment based on biological and genetic research sometimes leads to inadvertently losing sight of the bigger picture and the daily environment - where people live, grow, work, and love. It is this daily environment that has the most impact on people's health and is harming the health of too many individuals.
As healthcare professionals, we witness severe inequalities in our daily work, whether in clinics or in research. Homeless individuals may not follow a doctor's advice due to more pressing priorities. Transgender youth contemplating suicide is a result of an overly harsh society. Single mothers bear the responsibility for their children's health.
The role of a physician as a healthcare professional is not just to treat patients, but also to call attention and become an advocate for change.
Doctors, regardless of their legitimacy, carry considerable weight in their statements due to their social status, and it should not be wasted.
I regret not speaking up in Zimbabwe and have made a vow to myself. As the Commissioner of Health for New York City, I will make full use of the opportunities available to me, raise awareness, and call for collaboration to improve healthcare disparities.
I will also confront racial discrimination. Please lend a hand as well. When you stand up against gender discrimination, I will also support you. I will support you in addressing any form of inequality.
Now is the time for us to stand up and collectively speak out against structural inequalities.
You don't need to know all the answers to call for change.
It only requires courage.
The health of our patients and all of us is at stake.
